data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — work identically in .NET 8 and require no migration.

That said, for a .NET 8 modernization I'd recommend replacing the manual `Thread` usage with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`, which give you better resource management and built-in cancellation via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
        {
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), token);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation (the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`) should you need it in the future.
